  "prompt": "How many units can a 1 MW solar power plant produce in a whole day?",
  "response": "To determine how many units (kilowatt-hours, kWh) a 1 MW solar power plant can produce in a whole day, follow these steps:\n\n1. **Understand the Capacity:**\n   - 1 MW = 1,000 kW (kilowatts).\n\n2. **Determine the Average Daily Sunshine Hours:**\n   - The number of sunlight hours varies by location. On average, many regions receive about 4 to 6 hours of effective sunlight per day. For this calculation, let's assume 5 hours.\n\n3. **Calculate the Daily Production:**\n   - Daily Production (kWh) = Capacity (kW) \u00d7 Sunshine Hours.\n   - Daily Production = 1,000 kW \u00d7 5 hours = 5,000 kWh.\n\nSo, a 1 MW solar power plant can produce approximately **5,000 units (kWh)** in a whole day, assuming an average of 5 hours of effective sunlight.\n\n\\boxed{5000\\ \\text{kWh}}",
